<div id="review_2553491291" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2553491291" />
    <a title="Laura" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/28753553-laura"><img alt="Laura" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1392577195p2/28753553.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2553491291?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Laura" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Laura" href="/user/show/28753553-laura">Laura</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2553491291" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17708352258101852150">The beauty about this novel for me was the insights into the psychology of post Franco Spain and the flashbacks to the civil war and the WW2 years. I do not know much about this country but having also read some of Orwell&apos;s work the book gave me greater insights into this chapter of European history. Because I have never stopped to think about the consequences of a split population down the Fascist /Communist lines and what this can do to families. Only once was I struck by a statement from a Sp</span>
  <span id="freeText17708352258101852150" style="display:none">The beauty about this novel for me was the insights into the psychology of post Franco Spain and the flashbacks to the civil war and the WW2 years. I do not know much about this country but having also read some of Orwell's work the book gave me greater insights into this chapter of European history. Because I have never stopped to think about the consequences of a split population down the Fascist /Communist lines and what this can do to families. Only once was I struck by a statement from a Spanish acquaintance that hers was a 'deeply historically socialist family' and I understand now that this takes on a whole different significance in a Spanish context. Grandes writes beautifully, and although I agree with some reviews here that the book is too long, I liked the circularity of the story, the ways she works backwards and forwards, joining the chapters to give the reader the background to the future actions and protagonists, a fragmented timeline, dialogue, and interior monologue delivered spectacularly. At one point I actually thought the book had somehow the Shakeapearean ingredients of the Romeo and Juliette story, but the motivations behind the actions, the greediness of two of the key characters make it a more realistic story, squalid monetary motivations rather than reputation and credibility driving the main characters. All in all a great automn read!</span>
  <a data-text-id="17708352258101852150" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


